        "text_color": "#333333",
        "meta_color": "#666666"
      }
    },
    "rich_text_intro_002": {
      "type": "vl-rich-text",
      "settings": {
        "subheading": "Your Skin Changed. Your Foundation Didn't.",
        "content": "<p>After 40, your skin undergoes real physiological changes. The protective barrier thins. Oil production drops. Sensitivity increases. Yet most women are still reaching for the same foundations they wore a decade ago — formulas designed for younger skin that can actually accelerate the signs of ageing.</p><p>We spoke to board-certified dermatologists about the foundation mistakes they see most often — and the simple changes that make the biggest difference. No product pitches. Just the science they share with their own patients.</p>",
        "bg_color": "#ffffff",
        "heading_color": "#000000",
        "text_color": "#333333",
        "link_color": "#5C1A33"
      }
    },
    "image_text_tip1_003": {
      "type": "vl-image-text",
      "settings": {
        "image_asset": "lp-derm-foundation-reason-1.jpg",
        "image_alt": "Woman gently touching her face, healthy skin texture",
        "image_caption": "Your skin barrier changes significantly after 40.",
        "heading": "1. Your Skin Barrier Is Thinner Than You Think",
        "text": "<p>After 40, the outermost layer of your skin — the stratum corneum — begins to thin. It loses roughly 10% of its protective capacity every decade. This barrier is what keeps moisture in and irritants out. When it weakens, everything changes.</p><p>Most foundations contain ingredients that actively compromise this already fragile barrier. Denatured alcohol evaporates moisture. Synthetic fragrances trigger low-grade inflammation. Heavy silicones trap bacteria against skin that can no longer defend itself efficiently.</p><p>Dermatologists recommend formulas with hyaluronic acid, ceramides, and vitamin E that reinforce the barrier while providing coverage. Your foundation should be the best thing you put on your face, not the worst.</p>",
        "bg_color": "#ffffff",
        "heading_color": "#000000",
        "text_color": "#333333"
      }
    },
    "pull_quote_barrier_004": {
      "type": "vl-pull-quote",
      "settings": {
        "quote": "Most women who think they have a skin condition actually have a foundation problem. The barrier is being compromised every day by ingredients their skin can no longer tolerate.",
        "attribution": "Board-Certified Dermatologist",
        "bg_color": "#F5EDE8",
        "quote_color": "#333333",
        "accent_color": "#5C1A33",
        "attribution_color": "#666666"
      }
    },
    "rich_text_tip2_005": {
      "type": "vl-rich-text",
      "settings": {
        "subheading": "2. The SPF in Your Foundation Is Doing Almost Nothing",
        "content": "<p>Dermatologists have a phrase for it: <strong>\"SPF theatre.\"</strong> It describes the false sense of security most women get from the SPF rating on their foundation. SPF 15. SPF 20. It sounds protective. It isn't — at least not the way you're using it.</p><p>To achieve the advertised SPF level, you'd need to apply roughly <strong>seven times</strong> the normal amount. A thin, blended layer of SPF 20 foundation delivers, in practice, an SPF of about 2 to 4. That's functionally useless against UVA rays — the ones responsible for wrinkles, sagging, and age spots.</p><p>The solution isn't to stop wearing SPF foundation — it's to choose one that treats sun protection seriously. Look for broad-spectrum UVA/UVB filters with physical blockers like zinc oxide or titanium dioxide at concentrations that work at normal application thickness.</p>",
        "bg_color": "#ffffff",
        "heading_color": "#000000",
        "text_color": "#333333",
        "link_color": "#5C1A33"
      }
    },
    "image_text_tip3_006": {
      "type": "vl-image-text",
      "settings": {
        "image_asset": "lp-derm-foundation-reason-3.jpg",
        "image_alt": "Foundation bottles with anti-aging marketing labels",
        "image_caption": "The 'anti-aging' label lets brands charge 30% more for the same formula.",
        "heading": "3. 'Anti-Aging' Foundations Are Usually Just Marketing",
        "text": "<p>The beauty industry discovered something lucrative: put \"anti-aging\" on the label and women over 40 will pay 30% more for essentially the same formula. Dermatologists will tell you the vast majority contain active ingredients in concentrations too low to have any measurable effect.</p><p>Real results require specific ingredients at specific concentrations. Retinol needs 0.1% minimum. Niacinamide works at 2-5%. Most \"anti-aging\" foundations contain trace amounts — legally sufficient, dermatologically useless.</p><p>Your foundation is on your face for 10-14 hours a day. That's an enormous treatment window being wasted by formulas that promise everything and deliver nothing.</p>",
        "bg_color": "#ffffff",
        "heading_color": "#000000",
        "text_color": "#333333"
      }
    },
    "pull_quote_treatment_007": {
      "type": "vl-pull-quote",
      "settings": {
        "quote": "Your foundation is on your face for 10-14 hours a day. That's an enormous treatment window being wasted by formulas that promise everything and deliver nothing.",
        "attribution": "",
        "bg_color": "#F5EDE8",
        "quote_color": "#333333",
        "accent_color": "#5C1A33",
        "attribution_color": "#666666"
      }
    },
    "rich_text_tip4_008": {
      "type": "vl-rich-text",
      "settings": {
        "subheading": "4. You Might Be Allergic to Your Foundation and Not Realise It",
        "content": "<p>Low-grade contact dermatitis from cosmetics is one of the most underdiagnosed conditions in women over 40. The symptoms don't look like a typical allergic reaction — no dramatic rash or swelling. Instead: <strong>persistent dryness</strong> that no moisturiser fixes. A slight roughness. Occasional redness that comes and goes.</p><p>The culprits are usually preservatives (methylisothiazolinone, formaldehyde releasers), fragrance compounds (up to 200 individual chemicals under a single label listing), and certain dyes. Your skin tolerated these at 25 because your barrier was strong enough. After 40, that tolerance drops.</p><p>Switching to a hypoallergenic, fragrance-free foundation is one of the single biggest improvements dermatologists see. Within two weeks, the persistent dryness often resolves. The texture improves. The redness fades. It looks like a skincare miracle, but it's actually just removing the thing that was causing the problem.</p>",
        "bg_color": "#ffffff",
        "heading_color": "#000000",
        "text_color": "#333333",
        "link_color": "#5C1A33"
      }
    },
    "image_text_tip5_009": {
      "type": "vl-image-text",
      "settings": {
        "image_asset": "lp-derm-foundation-reason-5.jpg",
        "image_alt": "Woman over 50 with radiant, natural-looking skin",
        "image_caption": "The right foundation works for your skin, not against it.",
        "heading": "5. The Right Foundation Can Actually Improve Your Skin",
        "text": "<p>The belief that foundation is inherently bad for your skin is outdated. Modern foundations, when properly formulated, function as a leave-on treatment.</p><p>Hyaluronic acid at effective concentrations measurably increases skin hydration throughout the day. Niacinamide strengthens the barrier and reduces hyperpigmentation. Antioxidants like vitamin E neutralise free radical damage from UV and pollution.</p><p>Women who visit dermatologists looking ten years younger often share one thing: they wear foundation every day, but they wear <strong>the right one</strong>. A formula that hydrates, protects, and treats while providing natural coverage. It's the most powerful anti-aging tool hiding in plain sight.</p>",
        "bg_color": "#ffffff",
        "heading_color": "#000000",
        "text_color": "#333333"
      }
    },
